{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The answer is 9, for values "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"2,3,..., 10"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". Note that that "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"10^n > n^{10}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" for "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"n = 1, 11"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"10^n \geq n^{10}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" for "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"2\leq n\leq 10"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". We claim that "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"10^n > n^{10}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" for "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"n > 11"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". This can be shown by induction, since we have "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"n = 11"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" as a base case. If "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"10^n > n^{10}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"n \geq 11"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" then "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"10^{n+1} = 10\cdot 10^n > 10n^{10} = (n\sqrt[10]{10})^{10} > (n+1)^{10}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" "}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Taking the base 10 logarithm of both sides, we get "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"n\le\log n^{10}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":", or "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"n\le10\log n"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". We can divide so that the "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"n"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" is only on one side of the equation to get "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\frac{n}{\log n}\le10"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". The numerator of this fraction will increase faster than the denominator, so if we find that for some "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"k"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" that the fraction is equal to 10, then for all integers greater than "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"k"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":", the fraction will be greater than 10. This happens at "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"k=10"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". Thus, we have our upper bound. The lower bound, "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"2"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":", can be easily found by testing the original inequality with the first few values of "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"n"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\frac{n}{\log n}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" will continuously increase from 2 to 10, so all values in between will work as well. The answer is the number of integers between 2 and 10 inclusive, or 9."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

